# Architecture Boundaries

Follow the existing architecture of the project. Before implementing a feature, identify where similar functionality lives and follow the same pattern.

## Controllers

Controllers should receive requests, delegate work, and return responses. They should not contain business logic.

## Helpers

Helpers (`app/helpers`) should contain business rules and application logic. Prefer placing business logic in helpers rather than controllers.

## Database Access

Keep database access consistent with existing project conventions. Avoid placing database logic directly in controllers when the project already uses helpers, repositories or other abstractions.

## Validation

Reuse existing validation patterns. Do not duplicate validation logic across multiple layers.

## Responsibility Separation

Each layer should have a clear responsibility. Avoid:

* Business logic in controllers
* Validation spread across multiple places
* Database access mixed with presentation logic
* Large classes that handle multiple concerns

When multiple valid implementations exist, choose the one most consistent with the current architecture. Consistency is more important than introducing a new pattern.
